I don't like leaving bad reviews but I have to warn you guys think twice before dining at Quetzal of Brooklyn.  My main gripe is that they have a non-cash charge if you use a credit/debit form of payment. They don't advertise that fact clearly, hemming and hawing about an obscure sign near the register behind the counter. If only they would've advised me before swiping my card... Then they didn't even know how to refund it so that I could pay cash.  There was just a general malaise of inattentiveness and lack of professionalism from the front of the house to the kitchen/chef.  The food lacked seasoning and flavor that you would come to expect from a 'Dominican styled restaurant'  I should have taken it for a sign that the place was empty around lunchtime, and we all know in NYC if a restaurant is Poppin' there will be a long line of people wanting to eat.  The ambience seemed nice, clean, a few small tables, all empty of course.  Spanish cuisine for this neighborhood is in short supply so Quetzal seems like a great idea if albeit poorly executed.

-1 star did not feel welcomed to the restaurant at all. Pretty disorganized when taking orders and it is asking for disaster when orders get messed up.  Other than that, the food is standard from the Dominican food up in Harlem and Mexican food up in Harlem as well. Now, their burritos are subpar and chicken is very dry in the burritos. I would say Chipotle has more flavor than their burrito, and the price is similar. If I were to pick a place for burritos, Chipotle is better for just a buck more, it is not dry as much as the chicken in the burrito.  The interior of the restaurant is very small, three tables, 6 chairs and two more spot near the window. Would not suggest to bring big groups of friends there to eat, but it is a take out place.  Would I tell people to go there? Not likely, this place is definitely not worth driving to if your from Queens/Bronx/Manhattan. However, if you are from Brooklyn near the area, it is worth to check it out if you have not tried any Spanish food at all or to satisfy your Spanish food cravings.  Quetzal > Taco bell hands down and about the same or if not worse than Chipotle.  The sanitation grade is pending as of 10/9/2014 for those interested in that.
